## Current Phase Requirements — Dresser Calculator (MVP)

### Must Have (blocks launch)
- Input form: overall dresser dimensions (H × W × D), number of drawer rows, number of drawer columns, material thickness, available board widths
- Output: complete cut list with piece names, quantities, and dimensions in imperial fractions (to 1/16")
- Output: board shopping list with standard dimensional lumber names (e.g., "1×8"), quantities, and lengths
- All nominal-to-actual lumber size conversions use US standard sizes
- Input validation: impossible configurations (e.g., drawers taller than cabinet interior) are blocked with clear error messages
- Project saves to local storage and restores on return
- Output is printable / print-friendly

### Should Have (launch quality)
- Fraction input that guides users (e.g., whole number + fraction selector, or smart parsing of "3 1/2")
- Real-time cut list preview that updates as dimensions are entered
- Named project (e.g., "Bedroom Dresser") for local storage identification

### Could Have (post-launch)
- Export cut list as PDF or plain text
- Basic onboarding / welcome screen for first-time users
- "Report a problem" feedback button

### Won't Have (this phase)
- Multiple furniture types
- User accounts or remote storage
- Metric units
- 3D visualization

## User Stories — Dresser Calculator

1. As a hobbyist woodworker, I want to enter my dresser's overall dimensions so that the tool knows the outer boundary of my build.
2. As a user, I want to specify how many rows and columns of drawers I want so the tool can calculate drawer box dimensions.
3. As a user, I want to select which board widths I have available at my local lumber yard so the shopping list reflects what I can actually buy.
4. As a user, I want to see a cut list with every piece labeled, quantified, and measured in inches and fractions so I can mark and cut lumber without doing math.
5. As a user, I want a shopping list that tells me exactly how many boards of each type to buy so I don't over- or under-purchase at the store.
6. As a user, I want the tool to warn me if my drawer configuration is physically impossible so I can fix the inputs before wasting time.
7. As a user returning to the tool, I want my saved project to load automatically so I don't re-enter everything from scratch.

## Acceptance Criteria — MVP Complete

- [ ] A dresser with standard configurations (2×3, 3×3, 2×4 drawers) produces correct, verified cut lists
- [ ] All measurements display as imperial fractions to 1/16" — no decimals in any output field
- [ ] Shopping list references only real, buyable US dimensional lumber names
- [ ] At least 3 edge case configurations are tested and handled gracefully (e.g., single drawer, maximum drawers, non-standard thickness)
- [ ] Project saves and restores across browser sessions
- [ ] Output is verified in print preview

## Prioritization Guardrail

Before adding any feature or furniture type, ask: **Does this help a hobbyist produce an accurate cut list for a dresser today?** If no, it belongs in a later phase. Bring scope decisions to this agent before building.

## How to Respond

- Lead with current phase scope — always orient to where we are in the roadmap
- When a new idea comes up, immediately classify it: which phase does it belong to, and why?
- Write acceptance criteria in checkable, pass/fail format
- Flag when the team is working on Phase 2 problems while Phase 1 isn't done
- Keep requirements grounded in the user's actual job: plan a furniture build, get accurate lumber quantities
